               OPEN            Dislocation-Grain Boundary\par
Data Descriptor                Interaction Dataset for FCC Cu\par
                               Khanh Dang 1, Sumit Suresh2, Avanish Mishra                  3\par
                                                                                                , Ian Chesser4, Nithin Mathew3,\par
                               Edward M. Kober3 & Saryu Fensin2 \u9993?\par
\par
                               Interactions between dislocations and grain boundaries play a major role in controlling the strength\par
                               and ductility of structural materials. Experimentally, assessing and probing geometric and stress-based\par
                               criteria at the local level for dislocation transmission through grain boundaries remains challenging.\par
                               Therefore, there have been many efforts to systematically generate datasets of dislocation-grain\par
                               boundary interactions (DGI) via computational models such as molecular dynamics simulations. So\par
                               far, most DGI datasets have focused only on the subset of nominal minimum-energy grain boundary\par
                               structures, which limits their applicability, especially to materials processed far from equilibrium. We\par
                               present a comprehensive database of dislocation-grain boundary interactions for edge, screw, and 60\u176?\par
                               mixed dislocation with 330 <110> and 257 <112> symmetric tilt grain boundaries (total of 587) in\par
                               FCC Cu consisting of 73 minimum-energy grain boundary structures and 514 metastable structures.\par
                               The dataset contains the outcomes for 5234 unique interactions for various dislocation types, grain\par
                               boundary structures, and applied shear stresses.\par
\par
\par
\par
                               Background & Summary\par
                               Designing structural alloys with both high strength and excellent ductility remains one of the grand challenges\par
                               in materials science and engineering. One strategy that has proven effective in certain alloys is known as grain\par
                               boundary (GB) engineering, which involves manipulating the GB network via the introduction of high densities\par
                               of specific GBs such as coherent twin boundaries1\u8211?3. At the core of this strategy is the role that GB structure\par
                               plays in determining the outcome of dislocation-GB interactions (DGI). For a similar applied stress state, some\par
                               boundaries may block or absorb dislocations, leading to strain localization, while other boundaries promote\par
                               transmission. As a result, the DGIs alter the strength and ductility of a material depending on the volume frac-\par
                               tion of boundary types in the material4\u8211?6.\par
                                   Macroscopically, the Hall-Petch relationship hypothesizes that material strength can be increased by decreas-\par
                               ing the grain size due to an enhanced effect of dislocation blockage (which we refer to as pinning) as the density\par
                               of GBs is increased7. This relationship captures the effects of average grain size on yield strength without con-\par
                               sidering local GB structure. There are many situations where local GB structure impacts mechanical behavior,\par
                               especially far from equilibrium. For instance, Fensin et al. showed that only certain boundaries can avoid void\par
                               nucleation under shock loading by dissipating stress through plastic deformation8. Simulations and experiments\par
                               of irradiated metals demonstrate that non-equilibrium GB structures may have a higher sink efficiency than\par
                               well-annealed GBs9,10. Other examples of the impact of GB metastability on mechanical behavior can be found\par
                               in a recent review11.\par
                                   For DGI, the role of GB structure on the dislocation transmissibility remains unknown despite many exper-\par
                               imental, theoretical, and computational efforts over the past few decades. Microscopic geometric and stress\par
                               criteria for dislocation transmission through grain boundaries, such as minimizing the angle between the inter-\par
                               section lines of the incoming and outgoing dislocations or maximizing the resolved shear stress on the outgoing\par
                               slip system, have been proposed and experimentally validated6. One of the commonly utilized geometric param-\par
                               eters for examining slip or dislocation transmission across GB is m\u8242?, which assesses the slip system degree of\par
                               coplanarity12. However, similar to the Hall-Petch relationship, these criteria fail to capture the role of GB struc-\par
                               ture and the local atomic arrangement on GB-dislocation interactions.\par
