\par
                                 The lack of high-fidelity DGI datasets with details about dislocation type, applied stress, and, most impor-\par
                             tantly, diverse GB structures, inhibits our ability to construct more accurate models for GB-dislocation interac-\par
                             tions. Experimentally, it remains challenging to systematically and efficiently generate these datasets.\par
                             Computationally, most DGI datasets are limited in the number of data points since these have previously\par
                             focused only on a subset of grain boundary structures or dislocation types13\u8211?18. For instance, Cheng et al.13 stud-\par
                             ied the interactions between edge dislocations and [110] symmetric tilt grain boundaries (STGBs) such as \u931?\par
                             3(112), \u931?9(114), and \u931?9(221) in W. While this study found that the DGIs depend on the grain boundary struc-\par
                             ture and the exact location of the interaction within the grain boundary, it was challenging to propose a new\par
                             criterion for slip transmission due to limited data. Moreover, it is unfeasible to merge different DGI datasets into\par
                             a comprehensive one since boundary conditions usually vary and significantly affect the simulation results19.\par
                             Recent efforts to generate large datasets of GB structures by atomistic simulations have served as foundations to\par
                             further drive the research in DGI20\u8211?22. For example, one of the most cited datasets of computed GB structures\par
                             and properties is by Olmsted et al.20. This dataset contains 388 unique minimum-energy GB structures of Ni and\par
                             Al and their corresponding energies. A subset of this dataset (33 different FCC Ni bicrystals) was utilized for a\par
                             DGI study18. It was found that the minimum residual Burgers vector and the disorientation angle between the\par
                             two grains are strong indicators of DGI transmissibility. However, the GB structures in these previous studies\par
                             were simplified by choosing the minimum energy configurations, which are not necessarily observed in experi-\par
                             ments. It was shown recently that metastable GB structures (i.e., those which have higher energies than the\par
                             minimum configuration) can alter the outcome of the DGI23,24. Therefore, there is a need for a consistent and\par
                             comprehensive dataset that explores DGI as a function of dislocation character and GB atomic structure.\par
                                 The goal of this work is to fill this gap by establishing a comprehensive database of DGI in Cu as a model FCC\par
                             material. While the trends for the DGI dataset are expected to vary for different material systems, the approach\par
                             described in this work can be adapted for other material systems (especially those with FCC crystal structures). MD\par
                             simulations of DGI are systematically performed for different type of dislocations (edge, screw, and mixed 60\u176?),\par
                             GB structures (330<110 >and 257<112> symmetric tilt GBs with many metastable structures), and applied\par
                             stresses (250, 500, and 750 MPa). Altogether, this database includes 5234 unique dislocation - GB interactions,\par
                             which is the most of its kind currently. This comprehensive DGI database is expected to be useful to train AI/ML\par
                             models to predict DGI as a function of GB structure, dislocation type, and applied stress.\par
\par
                             Methods\par
                             Workflow overview.           The data and simulation workflow used to characterize and obtain DGI via MD simu-\par
                             lations consists of three steps as shown in Fig. 1: (i) First, GB structures (including metastable states) are gener-\par
                             ated using the standard \u947? -surface approach22,25. Dislocation dipoles are constructed using the displacement field\par
                             of an infinitely long dislocation dipole26. Both types of defects are generated via LAMMPS input scripts. (ii)\par
                             Second, dislocations are driven into the GBs under an applied stress19. The DGI outcomes are recorded and\par
                             indexed into a database. Details about the database, such as the parameters needed to reproduce GB structures as\par
                             well as DGI results, are described in the Data Records section. Each step in the workflow is described in more\par
                             detail below.\par
\par
                             Dislocation-grain boundary interactions via molecular dynamics simulations.                                     All\par
                             dislocation-grain boundary interactions in Cu are performed via the open-source simulation software Large-scale\par
                             Atomic/Molecular Massively Parallel Simulator (LAMMPS)27. The atomic interactions between Cu atoms were\par
                             modeled using an Embedded Atom Method (EAM) interatomic potential developed by Mishin et al.28. This inter-\par
                             atomic potential can accurately reproduce GB and dislocation core structures as well as their corresponding\par
                             energies28. Therefore, it has been widely used in DGI studies23,29,30. The simulation results are manually recorded\par
                             by analyzing atomic snapshots before and after the interaction via the visualization software OVITO and the\par
                             dislocation extraction algorithm (DXA)31. Simulation details about (i) the construction of the GB structure, (ii)\par
                             the DGI simulation setup, and (iii) the determination of the geometrical criteria (m\u8242?) are discussed in greater\par
                             details below.\par
\par
                             Grain boundary structures and energies. Figure 2 shows the simulation setup to generate the dataset. Both\par
                             <110> and <112> STGBs are generated using the \u947? -surface approach22,25. The X direction is always oriented\par
                             along the tilt axes, and the Y direction is normal to the GB plane (which can be found in the database for all\par
                             interactions). Periodic boundary conditions are applied in all three directions to allow for complete control of\par
                             the stress state. This simulation setup has been demonstrated to be efficient for DGI in previous work19. For the\par
