                             Data Records\par
                             The raw simulation data is not included in the database due to its inherently large size. Instead, the input files\par
                             and the GB structures to reproduce these results are included in the template.zip file that can be retrieved from\par
                             the Materials Cloud Archive repository35. Specifically, each misorientation contains subfolders of different GB\par
                             structures whose folder name is their GB energy. For each GB structure, there are two folders named \u8220?screw\u8221?\par
                             and \u8220?mixed\u8221? for screw and 60\u176? mixed dislocations, respectively. Each of these folders contains LAMMPS input\par
                             and data files to reproduce the dislocation-GB interactions. The dislocation-GB dataset of <110> and <112>\par
                             STGBs in Cu is reported in DisGBDatabase.xlsx and can be retrieved from the Materials Cloud Archive reposi-\par
                             tory35. The dataset contains 5234 unique dislocation-GB interaction entries (rows or data points). All the attrib-\par
                             utes (column headers) for these entries and their descriptions are listed in Table 1. The attributes \u8216?tx,ty,tz\u8217? and\par
                             \u8216?nx,ny,nz\u8217? define the orientation of the GB tilt axis and plane normal, respectively. These values represent the\par
                             macroscopic degree of freedom of the GB structure. Based on this, for each of the GB families, one can deter-\par
                             mine the \u8216?misorientation angle\u8217? attribute. On the other hand, the attributes \u8216?a,b,c\u8217? represents the indices of the\par
                             grid search for the microscopic degrees of freedom for the local grain boundary structures. Attribute \u8216?type\u8217? rep-\par
                             resents the type of incoming lattice dislocation. It can be either edge, screw, or 60\u176? mixed dislocations. Attribute\par
                             \u8216?applied stress\u8217? indicates the Schmid applied stress (pure shear stress in the slip direction on the slip plane) to\par
                             drive the dislocation toward the GB. Attribute \u8216?GBE\u8217? details the GB energy corresponding to the center grain\par
                             where the interaction happens. Finally, the attribute \u8216?reaction\u8217? describes the outcome of the interaction. Based\par
                             on simulation results manually analyzed via DXA in OVITO, the results are manually binned in one of the\par
                             following outcomes: (1) dislocation reflection from the GB, (2) dislocation absorption/pinning at the GB, (3)\par
                             dislocation partially transmitted through the GB when only leading partial can transmit and trailing partial is\par
                             pinned at the GB, or (4) dislocation fully transmitted through the GB. The outcome of DGI can also be unde-\par
                             fined if different outcomes occur simultaneously.\par
                             Technical Validation\par
                             Comparison with previous MD simulations.                 Figure 5 shows the summary of the DGI outcomes for\par
                             this database. For edge dislocations, very few transmissions are observed, even at the applied stress of 750 MPa.\par
                             Moreover, about 20 to 30% of edge dislocation was reflected/repelled from the GB. As the applied stress increased,\par
                             more edge dislocations get absorbed into the <112> GB instead of repelling. For screw and mixed dislocation\par
                             interactions with <110> tilt boundaries, the propensity to transmit (both partial and full transmission) increases\par
                             with increasing applied shear stress. The results from this database show that the dislocation transmissibility\par
                             generally follows: screw > mixed > edge.\par
                                 Figure 6 plots the results of DGIs for different applied stress, dislocation types, misorientation angles, GB\par
                             types, and GBE. From this plot, the transmission and repulsion cluster of data can be observed. This indicates\par
                             that macroscopic factors such as the misorientation angles are important to DGI. Overall, higher misorientation\par
                             angles make slip transmission more difficult, which was supported by many previous experimental results5,36\u8211?38.\par
                             For the same misorientation angle, there are metastable GBs with different structures and corresponding GBEs\par
                             whose reactions are different from each other23. Importantly, the effects are more evident for high applied shear\par
                             stresses (500 and 750 MPa). Together, this indicates that microscopic parameters such as the GB local structures\par
                             and dislocation types are also important to the outcomes of the DGIs.\par
