\par
                                 To further validate the database, DGI results for two of the most well-studied grain boundaries were checked.\par
                             They are the coherent and incoherent twin boundary (CTB and ITB, respectively) (misorientation angles of\par
                             70.5\u176? and 109.5\u176? as shown in Fig. 6, respectively) with simple structures and important role in deformation29,30.\par
                             Indeed, our results show that the screw dislocation absorbs into the minimum-energy CTB similar to previous\par
                             atomistic simulations using the same interatomic potentials29,30 and experiments where the coherent TB can\par
                             absorb the dislocation, thus providing resistance to slip transmission30. Furthermore, our variations in disloca-\par
                             tion transmission and pinning when 60\u176? mixed dislocations interact with ITB depending on the interaction sites\par
                             are also consistent with previous MD simulations39,40.\par
                                 Interestingly, in Fig. 6, the first-row data indicate that for a 109\u176? misorientation GB, screw dislocation\par
                             transmission occurs at 250 MPa, but not at 500 MPa. These results demonstrated that the outcome of the\par
                             dislocation-GB interaction for each interaction can be statistically varying. Indeed, for the case where transmis-\par
                             sion occurs at 250 MPa, the simulations were repeated twice with different initial sampling of the starting veloc-\par
                             ities. In both cases, the transmission does not occur, which is consistent with observation for higher stress at 500\par
                             and 750 MPa. These results further highlight the importance of including statistical variation in generating MD\par
                             simulation dataset, which was done in this work.\par
